# VM Disk Space Management — Fix & Strategy

## Problem

Every deployment creates a `leave-tracker-old-HHmm` folder on both VMs via the junction swap at **lines 706–707** (frontend) and **839–840** (backend) in `deploy-v2.ps1`. These folders were **never cleaned up**, accumulating ~20+ orphan copies on VM2 (10.172.19.15) as shown in your screenshot.

Additionally, `C:\deploy.log` and `C:\ops\leave-tracker-monitor\watchdog.log` grow indefinitely with no rotation.

## Root Cause

```powershell
# deploy-v2.ps1 lines 706-707 & 839-840 — runs EVERY deployment
$oldName = 'C:\leave-tracker' + '-old-' + (Get-Date -Format 'HHmm')
Rename-Item -Path 'C:\leave-tracker' -NewName $oldName -Force
```

The old Step 10 cleanup only pruned `C:\releases\v*` folders — it completely ignored the `leave-tracker-old-*` leftovers.

## What Changed

### 1. [deploy-v2.ps1](file:///c:/Apps/Leave%20Tracker/deploy-v2.ps1) — Step 10 Enhanced

The cleanup step now handles **4 things** instead of 1:

| Task | Retention | Before |
|------|-----------|--------|
| Clear `C:\deploy\` staging | 0 (always clear) | ✅ Already existed |
| Prune `C:\releases\v*` | Keep last 5 | ✅ Already existed |
| **Remove `leave-tracker-old-*`** | **Keep last 2** | ❌ **Was missing** |
| **Rotate logs** | **Keep last 500 lines** | ❌ **Was missing** |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Future deployments will now auto-clean. But you still need a **one-time cleanup** of the 20+ folders already on VM2.

### 2. [NEW] [cleanup-vm.ps1](file:///c:/Apps/Leave%20Tracker/ops/cleanup-vm.ps1) — On-Demand Cleanup Script

A standalone script you can run directly on any VM to reclaim space immediately.

## How to Clean Up Right Now

### Step 1: Preview (Safe — changes nothing)

SSH into VM2 (10.172.19.15) and run:

```powershell
# Copy the script to the VM first (from your dev machine):
scp "C:\Apps\Leave Tracker\ops\cleanup-vm.ps1" anthony.kimeu@10.172.19.15:C:\ops\cleanup-vm.ps1

# Then on VM2:
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File C:\ops\cleanup-vm.ps1 -DryRun
```

This will show you exactly what would be deleted and how much space you'd save.

### Step 2: Execute the Cleanup

```powershell
# On VM2:
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File C:\ops\cleanup-vm.ps1
```

### Step 3: Repeat for VM1 (10.172.19.16)

```powershell
scp "C:\Apps\Leave Tracker\ops\cleanup-vm.ps1" anthony.kimeu@10.172.19.16:C:\ops\cleanup-vm.ps1
ssh anthony.kimeu@10.172.19.16 "powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File C:\ops\cleanup-vm.ps1"
```

## Going Forward

| Concern | Solution |
|---------|----------|
| Old junction folders piling up | ✅ Auto-cleaned every deploy (keep 2) |
| Too many release versions | ✅ Auto-pruned every deploy (keep 5) |
| Logs growing forever | ✅ Auto-rotated every deploy (500 lines) |
| Need manual cleanup between deploys? | Run `ops\cleanup-vm.ps1` on the VM |
| Want to schedule it? | Create a weekly scheduled task (see below) |

### Optional: Schedule Weekly Cleanup

```powershell
# Run on each VM to auto-clean every Sunday at 2 AM:
schtasks /Create /F /RU SYSTEM /RL HIGHEST /SC WEEKLY /D SUN /ST 02:00 `
  /TN "LeaveTrackerDiskCleanup" `
  /TR "powershell.exe -NoProfile -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File C:\ops\cleanup-vm.ps1"
```
